charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising for the MacMillan nurses. 

My wife Carole is being looked after by the wonderful MacMillan nurses at the Derby Royal Hospital. Sadly Carole was diagnosed with an aggressive form of uterine cancer about three months ago and is now needing round the clock care. The nurses on the Nightingale ward have transformed her care and are making her last few weeks with us calm and peaceful Carole and I  can’t thank them enough and want to raise some money for them so they continue to help support people like Carole. We would be grateful for any donation that you would be able to provide.

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

Thank you.

Carole and Paul.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Walk 100km with your dog in November for Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Throughout November and the beginning of December, Bayley, Roscoe and I (Jamie and Mila may get involved from one walk to another!) will be walking 100km (hopefully more!) to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support.

This challenge is really important to me for many reasons. Like many of you, I have lost loved ones to cancer. I lost my dear Nan to cancer nearly ten years ago and I miss her dreadfully. And only two months ago I lost a dear, old friend of mine, James, who will always hold a special place in my heart. Everyone who gets cancer deserves life-transforming support and so with my loved ones in mind, I’m doing whatever I can to help Macmillan be there for anyone with cancer.

Any donation amount will be greatly appreciated. I’ll share updates of a muddy and wet Bayley and Roscoe (and myself probably!) and the walks as we complete the challenge. Thank you! 🐶🐾💚

P.s. Just for you James I will be putting the earbuds in and listening to Savage Garden, Bon Jovi and Greenday 🥰

Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support. 

There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support.

At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk/. 💚

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Cancer sadly affects so many people and families and has left huge holes in many people's hearts, which is why Macmillan Cancer Support is an important charity to us.

With our support they help people with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing specialist health care, support, and campaign for better cancer care.

We want to help Macmillan to continue with the amazing things they do, which is why we are taking part in a Skydive in Dubai on the 15th December 2021 to help raise money.

If Macmillan Cancer Trust is a charity close to you and you would like to support us, we would really appreciate your donations. This money can help the 3 million people in the UK living with cancer who are counting on Macmillan to support them with their physical, financial and emotional needs.

Hannah and Charlie x

eventName: Walking 100m with our dogs for Macmillan
story:
Hi ! 😊

My friend Sami and I are walking 100m with our dogs  in November for Macmillan cancer support. It is safe to say everyone has been affected by cancer one way or another, this will help us not only get active but also raise money for a great charity and cause. The miles will be on dog walks only not general daily steps. We will track our progress and share updates here and there 😊

Thanks for your support! 💚 love Sami, Ted 🐾 Emma and Codie 🐾

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Throughout November, my Romanian rescue dog Luna and I will be walking towards our target of 100km for Macmillan. From working as a Counsellor in a Hospice for the past 4 years, I have seen the devastating impact cancer can have on people and their loved ones. Macmillan is a really important charity that helps people affected by cancer emotionally, physically and financially but they can’t provide this support without the generosity of people like you. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Walk 100km in November with your dog for Macmillan
story:
Want to join me in supporting a good cause? I’m walking 100km with my dog Luna this November for Macmillan Cancer Support and every donation will make a considerable impact, regardless of whether you donate £5 or £500!  

There are around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more being diagnosed every year & right now millions of people are relying on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support. As a result of the coronavirus pandemic, Macmillan are facing a huge drop in income and 97% of their work is funded by people like us and they need our support now more than ever.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
The Brave who have just been diagnosed. The Brave who are currently under treatment. The Brave who have fought and have won. The Brave Doctors, Nurses, Researchers and Support Staff. And the Brave that fought but sadly didn't make it; My Dear Ravjibhai, My Dear Hemlata Aunt are just a few; for them all I am showing my support. I am also taking part in ‘Shave for the Brave’ for someone who means the world to me. He is currently undergoing treatment, and it is his Braveness that gave me the heart and strength to do this. I hope you can support this fantastic cause with kind words and a donation to help those that are far braver. 


I would like to say that my sons and nephew are also taking part which makes me really proud. Josh, Kaylan and Aaran. Love you lots Boys.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Our beloved mum, grandma, great-grandma, wife, sister, aunt, Godmother sadly passed away on Sunday 17 October.

We are very grateful for all offers of condolences and sympathy that we have received. It is very much appreciated.

We know a lot of people would like to send flowers but as a family we would prefer donations to acknowledge the great work that Macmillan Cancer Support do. We have experienced this first hand.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
I started out my 1000 mile challenge in January not long after Alison passed away.  Initially it was for my own personal challenge.  Now, having passed the 900 mile mark, I thought it would be good to complete the 1000 mile challenge in Alison's memory.  I will post weekly updates on my mileage and hope that some of my friends will support this worthy cause.  Thank you for supporting my fundraising. 


A bit about Macmillan ...

At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Garib Dass sadly passed away on Saturday 30th October 2021 at the age of 78, after a brief battle with lung cancer.

Garib was born on the 9th October 1943 to Lachman Dass and Nami in Manguwal, India. He migrated to England at the young age of 17 to work as a laborer, providing support for his family back home. He was one of five brothers who he loved immensely: late Tarsem and Naranjan, surviving brothers Piara and Gurnam. In 1964 Garib married Charan Kaur, and together they had 5 children: Rajinder, Surendra, Sarbjit, Balvinder and Harbans. 

He was an enthusiastic, family-oriented man who loved socializing. Garib always made time for everyone he knew, and lived a colorful life.  

In lieu of flowers people wishing to honor Garib's lifelong commitment to his family, can make donations to the Macmillan Cancer Support Charity - of which we are extremely grateful for.

His tireless love and devotion to his family were evident in his final moments.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Walk 100km in November with your dog
story:
We all tend to take life for granted - until the hard times hit. Those that have known me a long time know I’ve seen my fair share of lives affected by cancer. Whilst no one can change the past, we can help to ensure that when the hard times do hit, that the funds are there to support those that need it. 

By supporting this November campaign, both myself and Nelson can raise much needed funds, doing something we both enjoy - being in the great outdoors. We both have our waterproofs, so no matter the weather, we are always ready to be out (he does put the brakes on if it’s really chucking it down!) Off the lead Nelson is more likely to run 500km in the month, but together, and with my current foot injury, 100km is more than achievable. 

I’m sure we’ll both have an added bounce in our step, knowing that we can raise funds for Macmillan. I hope you can help us reach our target.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Dear All.

Every day in November I'm doing the daily 300 challenge.

33 press-ups, 33 sit-ups, 33 standing squats, 33 bicep curls with 5kg weight, 33 seated shoulder press with 5kg weight and 33 dumbell flys with 5kg weight.

Daily total will be 198 so I have to do 2 extra of one of them daily making the 300.

30 x 300 = 9000.

I've done this before and it's harder than it sounds so I'll need support and encouragement.

I'm doing this for Macmillan nurses who provide respite care for those passing of cancer - it's a charity very close to my heart.

So if you've got a spare quid or two throw it this way - and don't forget to tick gift aid so we get some tax back off out useless government too.

Take care of yourselves.

ade

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Two years ago we lost our friend and colleague Al Meadows to cancer. Al was a lovely human being and hugely supportive of the work we do for Macmillan. Each year, with the blessing of his wife and family, we will organise a 5k & 10k run to raise funds in his honour. We encourage everybody, especially those who knew Al, to take part in any way they can.

Thanks for making a difference!

Wing Commander Dave Savage on behalf of The RAF Cranwell Macmillan Cancer Support Team

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Cancer is shit.

Like almost everyone, i have seen first hand the work Macmillan do, and it’s incredible, a cuppa and a chat can go a long way, especially after diagnosis. 

my aim is to help one person have a better day after diagnosis by funding a support worker to help 

Anyone who knows me knows i hate exercise- and i REALLY hate squats. So i’ve decided to do 3000 of them in November, to raise a few quid for Macmillan.

anything you can give goes a long way - 0.52p will pay for a leaflet to help someone dealing with a diagnosis.£118 (my target) will pay for a support worker for one day.

check back and follow me on instagram to see how i’m getting on! 

From Macmillan; At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. eventName: Mike and Em’s Virtual  Mt Kilimanjaro challenge
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. I wanted to do something a little different to raise some money for a great cause that helped me when I was going through the hardest time . 

Last year I had a life changing operation due to having cancer.  As a consequence I’m not the fittest any more and with my dodgy leg this will be a big challenge for me, so I’ve asked Emma to be my wingman!  The challenge is for us to walk a virtual route up Mt Kilimanjaro of 97km over 5 weeks!  

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

story:
We want to help to keep the amazing work that Macmillan nurses do going.  When our mum had cancer they really helped her to feel better and not be so scared.  They help people when they are really frightened and need some help.  They need our help so that every person fighting cancer can have their wonderful support.

We both like running and a challenge, so we will be running a mile a day consistently this winter - even in the rain and on Christmas Day!

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Many of us have been touched by knowing people who have lived with cancer and, sadly watched those we love, die from cancer.  

During my lifetime I have lost my Nan to bowel cancer, my mother-in-law to lung cancer, my Aunty was diagnosed with breast cancer, I have friends, relatives, work colleagues and people I teach yoga to who have all been affected by this disease.

More and more people are surviving cancer but, sadly, many more do not. So, I have decided to run my first ever half marathon and raise money to help towards the research and support needed to help others fight the big ‘C’.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. At Macmillan, we give people with cancer everything we’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising event. 

We are taking part in a Stepathon in order to raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support. This will be done in our own time but together as a team. Our goal is to achieve 100k steps within the week and to push ourselves that little bit more physically in order to achieve this, just like those at Macmillan do everyday. 

If you have ever been effected by cancer or a loved one has, then please support this fund raising event by donating anything at all in order to help us achieve our target and to give back to those who are there to help us when we are in need.

Thank you in advance for your support & donations.

story: The three of us (Emma, Michelle and Lisa) try each year to take on a challenge and in turn raise awareness and money for charities close to our hearts. This year we are attempting 100 squats a day, per person throughout November for MacMillan. charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising.  I'm walking 100km with my dog Bella this November for Macmillan and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate £5 or £500. Every little bit helps. Thank you for your support. Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support. 

There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support.
At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk/. 💚

story:
We are saddened to share the news that Denise Piazza, proud wife and mum, passed away on October 23rd 2021 surrounded by her family.

Details of her memorial to be confirmed. Should you wish to express your sympathies, please make a donation in Denise's name to MacMillan Cancer Support, instead of sending flowers.

Denise was a keen fundraiser for MacMillan, having supported the charity on a regular basis and participated in events such as Walk the Walk and successfully climbing Macchu Picchu for the cause.

If you wish to speak to the family please contact Frank or Charlotte Piazza.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
eventName: Jess & Lucy do 500,000 steps in November
story: Thanks for supporting our fundraising challenge! Lucy and I will be walking a combined step count of 1 million … yes 1,000,000! So that’s 500,000 steps in November each. Why are we doing it? Because cancer affects so many of us. Both of us have sadly experienced family members getting or having cancer. Indirect contact with cancer can have so many negative effects, but support is what gets you through. 5 years ago I couldn’t even say the word cancer, but I’ve come to accept that working through any feelings around cancer have to be resolved, as how can I support someone with cancer if I can’t even say the word? Let’s do this!!!

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Thank you for supporting the Boyle family fundraising. We have set a modest target for this event and we are confident that our great friends will do all they can to help us exceed those expectations.  

It has been the bleakest of times for so many people over the last couple of years and we thought that we could spread a little positivity whilst doing what we do best and having the best of good times.  

Macmillan will be needed more than ever by those who have not had the access to care levels that were available pre-covid.  A cancer diagnosis is a shattering experience, life changing and earth shaking.  Macmillan nurses act as the stabilisers through those rocky waters and we would like to show our unending gratitude to them.  Their work does not stop at supporting the patient, the whole family benefit from their strength and wisdom. Their work is essential. 

The work that Macmillan do, we are in awe of, and we hope that you will dig deep in your pockets and help us spread a little comfort.  Then please bring yourselves along, enjoy a glass of mulled wine and a VERY warm welcome back to our home before dusting off your dancing boots and seeing if we still know how to do it!  

Let's Party!!!!!!

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
A year ago, my best friend ran 100km in a month to raise money for Macmillan and the amazing support they gave us and our families when our loved ones battled and ultimately lost the fight against cancer.

This month, we will say goodbye to Bev’s Dad, Frank Whiting, after he passed away following the same battle. The support offered from the Macmillan nurses was unimaginable and now it’s my turn to step up.

In memory of Frank, Gillan (Olivia’s Grandma) and Julie (Zach and Islas Grandma) I will cover 100km, in the wild or in the gym (eliptical or cycling) this month and ask for any donation you can afford to give to support this amazing charity.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
The 31st of October marks 7 months since my Mums diagnosis of Breast Cancer and December marks 6 months since her 10 hour mastectomy and reconstruction surgery. It has been a long hard 7 months but my Mum (and my Dad) have been amazing and always looking forward. I’m going to be running for a charity that means a lot to our family and help all those involved with cancer. 

I will run just over 5km every day over the month to raise money for this amazing charity. 5 is a special number as it took 5 skilled surgeons to help my mum during her operation. 

I have chosen Macmillan for my charity as cancer isn’t something that is fixed fast and it’s not just the physical cancer that is toxic but the effects that it has on  everyone’s mental well-being. The physical effects of cancer is horrible but the mental strain is also so impactful. 

As I run I will be thinking of my Mum and all she has been through but I will also think about the effects it has on all my family members. I will also think of the amazing staff and surgeons that helped her on her journey and still do. Finally another member of my family has just been diagnosed with cancer and I will also be running for him as we find out his course of treatment.

story:
The Great Septuple Challenge

1. Sheffield Half Marathon 13.1 Miles Sunday -27th of March

2. Leeds Half Marathon 13.1 Miles Sunday - 8th of May

3. Peak Challenge - 50 km Saturday and Sunday - 9th - 10th July

4. Dronfield 10K Monday - 29th of August

5. Peak District Challenge 50 km. Saturday - 17th of September

6. Sheffield 10 km September - Sunday - 25th of September

7. Yorkshire Marathon 26 miles Sunday - 16th of October

I lost my dad to lung cancer two years ago and a friend to skin cancer. The Macmillian was there for my dad and my friend. I want to raise as much money that is possible for the Macmillan Cancer Support. This challenge will also honour my father and my friend.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
CBRE are proud to partner Macmillan Cancer Support.

Living with cancer can be devastating at the best of times, but even harder as a result of the recent pandemic.  At Macmillan, we talk to people affected by cancer every day and for many, issues with money and mental health such as stress and depression, are their biggest worry.

Our partnership focuses on tackling financial hardship and loneliness together, helping Macmillan develop their telephone, online and virtual support services and to help thousands more people with much needed financial and emotional support.

The CBRE partnership is going to be more important than ever before, to help Macmillan do whatever it takes to support every single person living with cancer.

Cancer is not going anywhere.  And neither can Macmillan.

Join us in supporting Macmillan, so they can keep providing financial and emotional support to the millions of people that count on them.

If you would like to support us, any donation you make to our challenge will be greatly appreciated and will help Macmillan to support more people affected by cancer. Did you know that: £5.40 could fund 10 copies of Macmillan's cancer guide, £16 could fund Macmillan's online community for 1 hour and £32 could fund a Macmillan Nurse for 1 hour. Thank you so much for your support, we couldn't do what we do without you!

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
My brother's partner Emma, has been diagnosed with Breast Cancer and as she starts her chemo journey I wanted to set myself a challenge to do something positive to help raise funds for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

Emma is 38 and she has a 2 year old daughter Bonnie with my brother John along with their 14 year old stepdaughter Nicole, her life is going to be taken in a new direction while she attends 16 (15 more to go) sessions of chemo followed by surgery and radiotherapy. 

You're so brave,  you got this Em! Your girls, John and I love you #stronggirlclub #angelofthenorthwest

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story: Want to join me in supporting a good cause? As most of you will know I lost my Dad to cancer 5 years ago so I'm walking 100km with my dog Enzo this November for Macmillan and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate £5 or £500. Every little bit helps. Thank you for your support. Below is some information about Macmillan Cancer Support. There’s around 3 million people living with cancer in the UK today, and over 360,000 more are diagnosed every year. Right now, millions of people with cancer are counting on Macmillan for physical, financial and emotional support. At Macmillan, they do whatever it takes – last year was no exception. But they can't do it alone. Macmillan is facing a huge drop in income as a result of the coronavirus pandemic. Because 97% of their work is funded by people like us, they need our support now more than ever. Visit their website to find out more https://www.macmillan.org.uk/. 💚

I know Macmillan were a great source of comfort to Gemma during her illness and this is why it is so important to raise money for this amazing charity.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Around 6 years ago I was diagnosed with testicular cancer.   I was extraordinarily luck, that it is very treatable and I was diagnosed exceptionally early.

Earlier this year I was given the all-clear after 5 years of follow-up.  For that I am truly grateful. 

Movember is normally about prostate cancer awareness so I feel like I'm hijacking it a bit.  But this is personal, and as Macmillan were fantastically supportive I'd like to support them.  I, fortunately, hardly needed there services, except for reassurance in the early days, but I've witnessed many people including my own father 40 years ago, who needed Macmillan 's support to the very end.

I've set a very modest goal.  Please support me with a couple of pounds.

Thank you

story:
We’re taking part in a sponsored gaming marathon to support people living with cancer. From 12pm-6pm on Sunday 7th November we will work together to build a whole Wellbeing Village in Minecraft for cancer patients. 

 We know a lot of people suffer from cancer and that it is a sad time for them and their families. And a lot of resources have been refocussed on the Covid-19 Pandemic recently - we want to give a boost to those areas that have been forgotten. 

We each have just over £10 in our own charity pots which we will be donating ourselves to MacMillan but our target is £100 - please help us reach it! Thank you. Charlie and Eoin

story:
Support the team from EBC in their charity erg against Exeter by donating to Macmillan! We're aiming to row as far as we can as a club over 6 hours, with an aim to row further than Exeter.  

As a club we'd strongly like to support Macmillan due to their hard work in supporting people through their cancer journeys. As some of you will know, Mary, one of our coaches, has been fighting cancer this year and we want to show her our support as a club. Mary has dedicated so much of her time to us, our fitness, and the boat club and many of you will have come to her circuits which she continued to run even into her recovery. Mary has spent countless hours helping us improve on and off the water and so we want to use that fitness to support Mary and Macmillan on the erg!

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising, it really means a lot. By the end of November I’ll either be able to barely walk or I’ll have buns of steel! But most importantly, hopefully I’ll have raised a good amount of money for Macmillan Cancer Support. Like so many of us, I’ve had friends and family battle this disease - some have won, some have lost, sadly mostly the latter. Macmillan offers fantastic support to people, and their families, in the scariest times and we need to ensure their vital help can continue. 

In case you don’t know what Macmillan do…

story: Thank you for supporting JustGiving Page. My fundraising challenge will be 100 squats a day, for every day in November to raise some money for Macmillan Cancer Support. Macmillan Cancer Support have a very special place in my heart because they provided priceless support for my Auntie Julie when she was battling her Leukemia diagnosis 11 years ago. story:
The Strong & Wild gang are doing 100 squats a day during the month of November for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

If you would like to support us, any donation you make to our challenge will be greatly appreciated. This is a cause very close to our hearts as quite a few of our members have been through cancer treatment, had a family member go through it and one of us going through treatment right now. #Macmillancancersupport has been there from the beginning.

Here are our Squatting Champs:

charity.description:
The nation’s leading first aid charity.
Every year, more than 400,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes.
Our volunteers provide first aid in their communities and thanks to them fewer lives will be lost needlessly. 
Raise money. Help save lives. Be the difference.
charity.name: St John Ambulance
eventName: St John Ambulance – Rushall All Services Unit Fundraising
story:
As a charity with a long history of serving humanity, we are proud of our past, our role in the pandemic and excited about creating a healthier, safer, brighter and more resilient future.

This winter may be our toughest yet and I am helping to bring some community spirit by sharing my sparkle by supporting St John. 

St John volunteers treat and transport thousands of patients each year, and in times of crisis we are England's national health reserve.  

During the pandemic our skilled and highly trained volunteers are working long shifts supporting sick people and their families, in hospitals, in ambulances and at home. We are proud to be working alongside the nations ambulance trusts and in hospitals around the country.

"I enjoy helping people and its what I have been training to do. Its very rewarding personally knowing that my colleagues and I are making a difference to peoples lives when they most need it." 
Tom Willis, volunteer 

Will you support me and help make a difference?

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
St John Ambulance empower communities to step forward in the moments that matter to save lives.  
Every year, more than 800,000 people learn how to save a life through our training programmes, including hundreds of thousands of young people. 

Our ambulances are a familiar sight at public events and our volunteers give many hours of their own time to provide first aid in their communities, keeping people safe at events, and working alongside the NHS in response to 999 calls. 
The importance of St John Ambulance cannot be overestimated. It can quite literally make the difference between a life lost and a life saved.

story:

Thanks!

story:
My mum sadly fell asleep on 15th October 2021 which has left my Dad, my sister, myself and the rest of our family completely and utterly devastated.

We have learned that she passed away due to Coronary Arterial Thrombosis. As a result, in lieu of flowers at her funeral we are kindly requesting that people make a donation to The British Heart Foundation instead to assist with their research and development of treaments to combat a wide range of heart issues.

Any amount that we raise would be a great comfort to us as a family in knowing that your donations may help to save other peoples lives.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

So once again I'm taking on a challenge in memory of my brother Lee who passed away 11 years ago on the 10th November. This year I will be running 4 miles everyday throughout November. 

This year has been a difficult one as our Mum went into cardiac arrest in May, my brother Nathan and her partner Geoff ultimately saved her life performing  CPR until the paramedics arrived with the defibrillator. After 2 separate intubation's on ICU and a total of 9 weeks on Coronary Care she was discharged. After undergoing several tests Mum has been diagnosed with Long QT syndrome which is a heart condition that only presents itself when a person goes into cardiac arrest or if you are tested for it because a family member has it. Myself, my sisters, brother and Nephew have all been advised to have tests carried out to make sure none of us have the same condition. Between Lee's diagnosis 41 years ago and now it has become apparent that Long QT is linked with my brothers heart defect. This is why I will continue to fundraise for the BHF so they can continue to make scientific breakthroughs. This challenge won't be easy, the anxiety after nearly losing our Mum has prevented me from running as regularly as I usually do. I also stopped my 10 mile training and didn't participate in the York 10 miler as I was worried it may trigger something. This also meant I couldn't raise money for the BHF. So it's definitely going to be a challenge.

 On reflection I've realised that I need to keep my own heart healthy regardless of the outcome of the tests  I also want to keep Lee's memory alive and continue to contribute to the BHF so their research will hopefully prevent other families suffering at the loss of a loved  one. Let's keep hearts beating ❤ Please donate if you can ❤

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our JustGiving page.

We are heartbroken to have lost the main lady in our lives.  Everyone who knew Jane would say though she be but little she is fierce.

Jane Boulton was an amazing wife to Tony,  mother to Chris, Stephen, Anthony and Nicola, sister,  as well as much loved Sister, Auntie, Nan and Great Nan.

 Despite the heartbreak of losing her beloved Tony last year due to Covid-19, Jane proved what a strong woman she was overcoming many physical and mental obstacles such as, her own health difficulties, living alone for the first time, fighting her mental health, and navigating all of the adulting tasks which for many years Tony had dealt with. 

Jane passed away on Tuesday 26th October 2021. She had unknowingly had a hole in her heart for many years. She became unwell Monday evening, was blue lighted to Manor Hospital where her life was saved after she arrested for several minutes. Despite being transferred to New Cross Hospital for Emergency surgery the following day Jane sadly passed away during surgery. The care that Jane received from Rhesus and the staff on the ward at B9 is something that we will never forget.

As a family, we are asking for any donations to be for the amazing charity The British Heart Foundation. We hope to raise money in memory of Jane, and to continue to fund life-saving research and help many other families.  We hope that Jane is at peace now with her soul mate Tony.

When the funeral has been arranged I will update this page with all the details. 

Thanks for taking the time to read and share this. 

Sophie

story:
'Do as I say, not as I do'. 

This group of self-confessed sweet-toothed dentists are hoping to get a taste of their own medicine this coming month by giving up chocolate to raise money for the

 British Heart Foundation.


Seven million people in the UK live with heart and circulatory diseases, and these diseases are responsible for more than quarter of all deaths. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. 

We are hoping that the money raised will help lead to a  future free from the fear of heart and circulatory diseases. A world without heartbreak.

Please give what you can to help us hit our target,  we are so grateful for your support.

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

eventName: Cumbernauld Volunteer Fundraising Group 12 Dogs of Christmas Fundraiser
story:
This Christmas,  help me give a life-changing gift to someone with sight loss.

Together we could fund 12 new guide dog partnerships. Each guide dog could give someone with sight loss the gift of confidence to get out and about safely. 
Whether helping their owner visit family or friends, or to shop for that special surprise gift for a loved one. Your fundraising will help provide life-changing practical support not just at Christmas, but all year round.

From enjoying every magical Christmas moment, to the simple festive pleasures that most people take for granted. Our ambition is a future where everyone with sight loss is able to live the life they choose.

Thank you.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
• To those that don’t know yet: I am trying to raise £5000 to name a puppy after my first Guide Dog  ‘Casa’ through the ‘Name a Puppy’ programme run by the Guide Dogs organisation itself.. I want another ‘Casa number 2’ to be trained to support a partnership with another blind or partially sighted person so they can have too what I had. My Casa is no longer working. She supported me for 10 years. At 13 1/2 (as of November 2021), she is happily enjoying a doggy retirement. .
I have to admit the scary fact that I will reach half a century myself this month. With this in mind I realise that Casa has been with me for over 1/5 of my life. It seems unbelievable in itself.

Casa continues to be the most blessed physical gift I have ever received. I am biased of course, but she has always been the most perfect dog in so many ways. I could go on and on about her working skills but I just want to leave you with these thoughts instead. Casa has been the friend I so desperately needed. My partner, soulmate, best girl, my bed companion, and so so much more. Casa taught me how to love, and to be loved-unconditionally.

I totally dread the final day which all dogs must reach but I am thankful for the time I have had with her now in doggy retirement, walking and playing in the park and visiting our favourite cafés.

Many of you will know that I have been fundraising for a while now. I had all sorts of plans for the main fundraising just before Covid hit. All my plans;, like the world, went pear shaped!

I wondered if I might take the opportunity of my 50th birthday to try and raise a little more towards the fund. I know I am sometimes lucky enough to receive gifts and cards to mark birthday occasions but this fundraising to help somebody else’s life instead is so so much more important. I know some people have already donated previously but if you were going to send me a gift or a card, please think instead about the future of a blind or partially sighted person desperately needing a guide dog and think of it as donating to their lives instead. As I said at the start I have to raise £5000. Just over £1400 has already been raised (including the gratefully received recent birthday donations through Facebook.) The aim here and perhaps to be creative is to suggest £63.50 as a representation of classes and mine combined age but let’s be daring and double it and aim for a £127! Instead

Every £1 or £2 which you would have spent on a card with account. Casa (who is currently next to me on my bed fast asleep) I’m sure, with thank you too.

Hopefully I will be able to work out how to add a few photos to this. If not, just think of the most beautiful black flat coat retriever cross labrador, with long silky ears, soulful brown eyes, a tail which I call ‘ thumper’ because Casa loves to  wag her tail and literally thump anything or anyone who happens to be near her,. A tail constantly sharing her happiness. I can’t forget one other infamous characteristic: the minute we stop at a cafe or to wait for a bus; her harness would come off and that became the signal to Casa it was time to reverse into the nearest person, friend or stranger and hope her back end would be tickled . Or perhaps even better (or worse); Turning onto her back, tail still working, legs in the air and a very toothy grin all over her face wanting her tummy tickled instead! This  is the Casa I know and love. A happy dog at her best.

Do I need to say anymore? except a big thank you.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
During November, I'm stepping out and stepping up by committing to walking 500,000 steps over the month, walking and running in the streets, in the gym and on events. I love getting out walking, but my busy schedule means this will be quite the challenge.

Thank you for your support. I've included information about Great Ormond Street Hospital and Children's Charity below.

Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive for life-changing treatments.

Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity raises money to enable the hospital to provide world class care and to pioneer new treatments and cures for childhood illnesses.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
eventName: I’m doing 500,000 steps in November for Great Ormond Street Hospital
story: We are a group of new mums who know all too well the concerns that parents have for the wellbeing of their children and the amazing work done by Great Ormond Street. As such, for the month of November, we are donning our trainers and gearing up our prams to attempt to take part in the 500,000 steps in November challenge. Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive for life-changing treatments. Every day, young lives hang in the balance as patients, families and staff battle the most complex illnesses. Every day, the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs that change the lives of thousands of children – and change the world. Despite the greatest challenges a child can face, the hospital is a place where being sick does not always mean being sad. And it’s a place where you’ll find – today and every day – some of the bravest people you could ever meet. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support, and every day is a chance for you to make a difference.

story:
Dear Donor,


Great Ormond Street Hospital is the largest centre for child heart surgery in the UK and one of the largest centres for heart transplantation in the world. 


Doctors and Nurses every day battle the most complex illnesses to give a better future for seriously ill children.


In April 1929 J.M. Barrie donated the copyright license of his Peter Pan works to the hospital.


Diana, Princess of Wales served as president of the hospital from 1989 until the last day of her life.


With warm regards,


Fernando.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
I am aiming to cycle 300 miles in 30 days to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children’s Charity. To put that into perspective - I will be riding the distance from Brighton to Blackpool!

This charity has always been close to my heart and I would like to raise awareness of the hard work and dedication that GOSH have to saving the lives of babies and children.

Monies raised will be used for the following:

- rebuilding and refurbishment of wards and medical facilities designed around children, helping the hospital treat more patients

- ground breaking research to find treatments for the most complex childhood illnesses

- advanced medical equipment for treating the toughest and rarest conditions 

- child and family support services that can ease the burden on families, raise spirits, and support children and young people through their treatment.

For anyone who knows me…this is a huge challenge. Just one gym class usually has me floored - so have fun watching me unable to walk for the entire month of November!  

Due to the cold weather, I will be making up my miles by a mix of indoor cycling on the weekdays (including spin classes), and outdoor cycling on the weekends. My aim is to complete 10 miles a day, however as a working mother, time is of the essence! So it’s likely I’ll be taking some days off in the week and be forced to double my miles on the other days. Overall, I promise I won’t make it easy on myself!  All cycles will be tracked and logged onto MapMyRun.

Wish me luck - and please donate..every £ and p counts to saving another life.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This November I am doing 500,000 steps for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children’s Charity.

Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) needs your support more than ever. Children still need to go to GOSH for treatment every single day. Due to the pandemic, children’s services have been significantly impacted, and the hospital's dedicated staff are working hard to offer treatment to patients whose non-urgent care was postponed.

By supporting GOSH at this time, you will help them deliver the practical and emotional support that parents and families need.

Your donations could help towards:

  • Family accommodation so parents and carers can stay close by while their children undergo treatment.
  • Support services including the hospital's dedicated Play team, which helps patients understand their treatment and cope with separation from peers and siblings.
  • The social work service and multi-faith chaplaincy team who provide families and staff with vital advice and support.

Government restrictions mean that only one parent is able to be in the hospital with each child, this restriction means that parents are having to take good and bad news on their own but they are also having to be a strong support for their ill child who is scared from the illness but also from being treated by nurses and doctors in masks and protective clothing. story:
For sure, I am not the most sporty and fit person on earth nor a runner by nature. Yet I have mastered collecting Corona kilos…and need to get rid of them asap. So, it’s about time to start the engine. Again. After I managed to complete the half marathon distance once, on a beautiful Friday morning, November 27, 2020 on the coast of Muscat, Oman. And in a decent time of 2h00m10s as well, I may rather proudly say. Unfortunately, I haven’t had the chance to enjoy such a run during a race. Next opportunity and to get back into the rhythm and shape: the London Landmarks Half Marathon on April 3, 2022! And my sporty goals are first of all to finish and, secondly, within 2 hours.

Most importantly, I hope you will keep me motivated in the (gradual!) run-up to and during the race by supporting me in my goal to raise funds for the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). The son of a dear colleague is currently being treated there for cancer. And I wish to support GOSH in improving its facilities. Not only for him and 600+ other children and young people who receive the best possible care on a daily basis. I also run for parents such as my colleague. From the time I was still a child and hospitalised for some years, I know how important proper facilities in and around hospitals are for parents as well, as they enable them to provide the best possible support to their children.

Although not having nor willing to have any influence on the spending by GOSH of the funds raised, I am sure your contribution like my own will come to good use in one way or the other. Many many thanks in advance for at least considering!

eventName: At least five million steps in 12 months
story:
YES, you have read the title correctly. This is my fourth sponsored charity event in 15 months and probably the most testing of all.

These began in May 2020 with a sponsored ONE MILLION STEPS IN 23 DAYS for NHS CHARITIES TOGETHER. A healthy 463 miles…….This was during furlough so I was able to walk an average of 20 miles+ per day without affecting my work.

Over my Christmas 2020 holiday I cycled (on a gym bike at home) the 874 miles distance from Lands End to John O’Groats to raise funds for Care Of Police Survivors (I’m a former cop with Grampian Police / Police Scotland).

In May 2021, by motorcycle, I rode the 516 miles of the North Coast 500 in 12 hours 45 minutes to raise funds for the Aberdeen Blood Bikes Charity NERVS. (I am a volunteer motorcyclist for them).

THIS event is slightly different as I’m raising funds for two fantastic charities, one close to where I live in Aberdeenshire, the brilliant ARCHIE FOUNDATION and the world famous GREAT ORMOND STREET HOSPITAL (GOSH).

I’m well aware of the ARCHIE FOUNDATION’S work which is the driving force behind fundraising for the Royal Aberdeen Children’s Hospital and helps transforms children’s hospital environments to make them more child friendly and sees nearly 35,000 children and young people each year.

hello@archie.org has answers to all of your questions about the work previously, currently and planned for the Grampian area (which is where I’ve asked my money raised by put to best use).

The second charity of GOSH sees an average of 619 children arrive from all over the UK each day. Similar to the ARCHIE FOUNDATION, GOSH support families and children, research into children’s health and fund vital life saving equipment.

www.gosh.nhs.uk

I would argue both are extremely deserving of my efforts and your generosity.

The reason for the FIVE MILLION step walk is quite simple. It doesn’t take any expensive kit, require spending time from home / work and aside from making thousands for the two charities, will help keep the pounds off as I’m 58 a few months and not getting any younger.

The addition to the two charities I am proud to announce my event is supported by BUTLIN’S. Yes the holiday resort company.

Their part came into being when my family spent a week at the Skegness resort. I’ve been a ‘Butlin’s’ kid all of my life and take my family there each year. Previous charity events I’ve completed over the years have been supported by Butlin’s and they have even donated holidays which were auctioned and raised many hundreds of pounds.

I know Butlin’s have sponsored GOSH for decades, and each year regularly donate in excess of £50,000. To this end, this was something I was happy to incorporate into my event.

My plan is to actually surpass the FIVE MILLION steps and carry on until the 12 months are completed and just see where I have ended up with the final figures.

The event began on Monday 19th July 2021 on our first day of our holiday, and will end next year on Tuesday 19th July 2022 again on our Butlin’s holiday where there will hopefully be a small media event, a few Redcoats to see me over the line and a very cold pint of Heineken!

FULL DISCLOSURE. I am not now, nor have I ever been in the employ, paid or unpaid of the ARCHIE FOUNDANTION, GOSH or Butlin’s or any of their partner companies.

HOW THE EVENT WILL BE CARRIED OUT.

Each day my steps are counted via Smart watch / app from the moment I’m out of bed, throughout my working day (I’m a plant operator in the quarry business), walking on my work breaks and each night after work, with an average daily target of at least 15,000 steps. Some days I’ll do more or less, but it’ll average out, especially over Christmas when I’m off for two weeks and be able crack on with many more.

The event has it’s own Facebook, Twitter and Instagram page.

story: On Tuesday 21st September my special friends Cara and Rob’s world turned upside down! Their beautiful baby girl Molly suffered 5 cardiac arrests and was rushed straight to Great Ormond Street Hospital. They were told to prepare for the worst and every day was touch and go. 2 weeks later they made the decision to turn her life saving machine off to see if her heart would cope and Molly showed her true strength and against all odds proved the doctors wrong and stayed stable! Each day since then she has shown the world what a fighter she is and remains in a stable condition. None of this would have been possible without the outstanding care of the team at GOSH. Cara, Rob and Molly’s future is completely unknown but all we do know is how bloody amazing the three of them are. As a friend it’s truly heartbreaking to hear and not be able to help so that is why I have decided to run the marathon to try and raise as much money as possible for this hospital so they can continue to support the Barbers in every way possible!! It is truly unimaginable what they are going through every day so please give all you can to this amazing cause and help Molly come home ❤️

charity.name: Cancer Research UK
story:
Hi! 

This month I will be doing 5km every day with the hope of raising money for both motor neurone disease and cancer research uk. I will be doing this along side working 60-70 hours a week and will not be including any distance I do in work. So wish me luck! 😂

Please donate anything you can, big or small, share me. Anything that will help try to raise as much money as possible for the great causes! 

I have chosen these two charities as both illnesses have affected my family recently. My dad (Robert) was diagnosed with cancer last year. Around the same time, my uncle David was diagnosed with motor neurone disease and after living with the horrible illness for just over a year, sadly passed away in may. 

Motor neurone disease (MND) is a terminal condition that takes over the brain and nervous system causing slurred speech, muscle weakness and difficulty eating and gets worse over time. 

Both illnesses are a heartbreaking diagnosis to receive and I would like to give back to these charities as they help support patients and their families and find cures, as well as in memory of uncle David. 

Thanks for any donations!!

story:
After a five year battle with cancer, on October 22nd 2021 Dad passed away peacefully in his own home with his family around him.

Dad battled hard for so long, supported by three things: the love of his family; the support of many wonderful organisations and healthcare providers; and through the miracles of modern cancer treatments, without which we would have lost him long ago.

Dad's funeral will take place on Tuesday 16th November 2021. Floral tributes on the day will be from the family and we ask that if you wish to make your own tribute in his memory, that you do so by donating to Cancer Research through this page.

Thank you,

Chris, Steve, Neil & Leigh  x

story:
Oh crikey I have left this til last minute…..Sometimes I sign up to things without thinking….. now I have to abseil down an 118ft castle wall this afternoon and I am not that keen on heights lol, luckily for me Duncan and boys are tagging along and we hope to raise a few pound for the wonderful work, care and support Marie Curie hospice provide. I hate hate hate asking for dosh but we would all agree the wonderful care Marie Curie provides for our loved ones is worth the price of a posh coffee or a slice of cake at your fave cafe …. We would be ever so grateful for any donation, every penny adds up ♥️ and probably my reaction to abseiling down a castle wall will be worth a few quid lol …. Gulp xx


Thank you everyone

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Lots of people have asked where they can donate to in memory of Monica.

Those of us who knew Monica , knew how much she hated hospitals, and after she had been in hospital in April her wish was to have no further admissions to hospital; she wanted to stay at home. In the final weeks of her life, support from Marie Curie meant that we were able to honour this wish.

During those final weeks, the support Monica (and we) received from Marie Curie nurses and carers eased us through a very difficult time. We are therefore are asking for donations so that other families can be supported as we were.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

During the month of November, we (Joanne, Danni, Darren & Bernardine) will be walking / jogging / running 100 miles each to raise vital funds for Marie Curie in memory of Pauline Corr. 

Marie Curie is a charity very close to our hearts, providing much support and assistance during the last few months of our mother's life.

Whilst the fundraising through this challenge is our small way to say thank you for the care and attention Marie Curie provided our family, we know it falls short of how grateful we really are.

To help us along this journey and give us the added drive and determination needed, we would love it if you could donate whatever pennies you can afford to this worthy cause

story:
Marie Curie is an amazing charity that has a very special place in my families life, as they cared for my Dad during his illness and particularly through the last days of his life.  I spent a lot of time in the Belfast hospice which was extremely difficult and a whole new experience, but it was made so much easier by the caring staff who worked tirelessly to make sure that we were all okay 24/7.  I got to see the work first hand from all of the lovely nurses and staff at Marie Curie and the hard work they put in to ensure everyone feels comfortable and at ease during a very anxious and uncertain part of our life. The staff were so supportive and went above and beyond to make sure not only my Dad, but that everyone in my family was okay which meant a lot. I can’t thank them enough, and all their hard work means so much to families just like mine and it will never ever be forgotten. It is so hard to put in to words how much this charity means to me and to be able to do something which allows me to give back such as this, will help them greatly by allowing them to carry on providing exceptional care to other patients and families, so whatever donation you give big or small, it will be greatly appreciated by both myself and Marie Curie.

Thank you so much for taking the time to read my story, Amy Dunne x

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

There really are no words to describe our beautiful, courageous, passionate mom. Those of you that truly knew her have described her as a living angel, gorgeous, always thinking of others, glam, a beautiful soul, non-judgemental, fun, loving, an inspiration and she's definitely one of the strongest people we have ever met.

Mom was first diagnosed with triple negative breast cancer in 2018 and underwent surgery, chemo and radio. This gave us some more time with Mom, unfortunately the disease returned October 2020 so Mom underwent a masectomy, she was then told she was NED in December, however the disease came back with a vengeance and since February our world fell apart. Mom amazed us by her strength and positivity in her last months. She loved her life, her devoted husband Johnny, kids and grandkids and didn't want to leave us. 

Marie Curie hospice and staff provided Mom and us the support we needed during Moms last weeks and we will forever be grateful for this.

Mom ALWAYS looked on the bright side of life, she really did and that is how we want to honour her memory by doing the same.

Thank you for your kind donations to support this truly fantastic cause.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last.

We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how.

Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
I am a Photographer and a UAL Alumni who has taken on the challenge amongst fellow students of raising funds for an amazing charity. We will be taking on a 6 day trek covering Machu Picchu's (Peru) mountain passes that are as steep and high as 4,600m.

Marie Curie supports people and their families who are living with terminal illnesses. They offer expert care and support to those who only have a limited amount of time left, whether that be at one of the hospices or in the comfort of their own home. They continue to support families after their loved ones have passed.

Whether it be a small donation of £1, every penny is appreciated greatly and will make the world of a difference. I want to conclude in saying no donations will go towards funding our trip (travel, accommodation, food etc.) and is directly funded to the charity. 

Nisha :)

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
I’m partnering with ‘choose a challenge’ as part of the Plymouth University RAG (Raise & Go) Team! 

Cycling from London 🇬🇧 to Paris 🇫🇷 while raising money for the amazing work of Marie Curie 🌼 caring and supporting the terminally ill and their families.

This challenge will take 4 days to complete, with 3 of those days being spent on the bike 🚴🏼‍♀️ cycling 280km! Starting from Greenwich Park (London) - Newhaven - Dieppe - Paris …crossing the finish line at the foot of the Eiffel Tower 🗼


What do Marie Curie do? 🌼

Marie Curie was established the same year the NHS was. It provides care and support to people with terminal illnesses and their families. They provide this care and support through information, nurses, hospice care, and helper volunteers.

What your donations can do:

- £24 pays for a call to their support line, meaning someone can receive practical information and emotional support.

- £90 pays for half an evenings care in a person's home.

- £180 pays for nine hours of nursing support in someone's home throughout the night.


About Just Giving:

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Sadly, my dear dad passed away at the wonderful age of 84, on Saturday 23rd October 2021 at 10.28am. 

His final couple of days and hours were not nice for him, and I can say that I am glad to know he is now at peace, reunited with the love of his life, Mary his wife and my mum. 

Those that knew dad over the years will know that he held many amazing life changing careers, one of which he was always proud to share ~ being RNLI Crew member, Helmsman and maintenance mechanic, during the years of 1970 to 1985, saving a total of 162 lives. 

His final wishes were for a private cremation to take place.  Therefore, it will be private flowers only from family, and I thought it appropriate to set up an RNLI fund giving page for those still wishing to gift. Being based at Mudeford in Christchurch, Dorset, this is also where he met my mum Mary,  hence I think it’s an apt cause to donate to. 

If anyone would like to pay their respects by leaving a donation then please do… any amount in my dads memory, is so appreciated. 

May you all raise a glass and give dad a farewell toast, as I am sure you all share very different stories and memories. 

This is for you Dad ~ you will be very dearly missed.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Our RNLI lifeboats in the South East protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
From the stunning Dorset, Sussex and Kent coastlines to the unpredictable tidal Thames, our favourite places in the South east are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 31 South East lifeboat stations is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
In 2010 the D-Class Inshore Lifeboat Ollie Naismith was officially named and went on service at Looe. The lifeboat was named after a popular local teenager Ollie Naismith who sadly died in a tragic road traffic accident in 2009. Ollies parents, Maxine and John Naismith spearheaded a fundraising campaign to raise the funds for the lifeboat which has gone on to save many lives in and around Looe including the life of Louis Webber, a young local lad who was of a similar age to Ollie. 

The lifeboat is now coming to the end of its operational life so the team at Looe Lifeboat station are teaming up with the Naismiths and Webber family to launch the Looe Lifeboat Appeal to raise the £78,000 required to provide a replacement lifeboat which will be named the Ollie Naismith II.

Your donation to this community appeal will help to fund this lifeboat which will continue the selfless work of our volunteer lifeboat crew in Looe.

Reuben has been asking to raise money for his favourite animals - monkeys and sheep! We couldn't find a combined monkey and sheep charity so have agreed to raise money for the WWF.

He's not particularly keen on running, but is really determined to complete and excited about the prospect of raising money for an excellent charity that helps protects the homes of monkeys.

If anyone could spare a few pounds to help motivate him round that would be great!

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
This year I've decided to set myself an ambitious goal. I'll be taking part in the Everest Base Camp Trek in aid of WWF. I'll be undertaking this challenging 11-day trek through the Nepal Himalaya to reach the iconic Everest Base Camp at 5,645m!

My challenge will support WWF, who are the world's leading independent conservation organisation with the mission to create a world where people and wildlife can thrive together. I'm supporting WWF because we are the first generation that knows we are destroying the world and the last that can do anything about it. Our planet is suffering but together we can make a difference and fight for our world.  

That is why any donation big or small, sharing my fundraising page, or even just spreading awareness of WWF is hugely appreciated! 

Thank you for all your support. 

If you'd like to find out any more information or join the fight for our world please visit https://www.wwf.org.uk/

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Dear family & friends,

This year I studied in my school about the importance of wild life and sea life. Learning that wildlife populations worldwide have declined on average by 68% made me sad since Wildlife helps in maintaining the balance of nature. Hence they need to be preserved.

I learnt about Organization - WWF - that helps in preserving the wild and Sea life. In my video I have prepared a project explaining the danger to wild life and sea life. I wish that we all join hands in preserving and love the beautiful nature and diversity of wild life and your contributions will help me together with WWF to achieve the goal. 


I sincerely hope that this little gesture of goodwill and sense of responsibility towards our own future will play an important part towards the cause that is now very dear to me.

Hope you will support me.

Love - Maya Kasmani

story:
Min Ji is a little girl who lives in London. She enjoys going to school, chasing her friends in circles, burnt toast at breakfast clubs, going on holidays and all the regular things that children do. When Covid-19 shut the schools down, like all other Year 2 children, she discovered the joy of solitude and her friendship with her soft toys transcended to a whole new level. With all the time in the world to herself, she started writing about her toy chicken going on an adventure around the world, based loosely on her pre-Covid holidays and the places that she may one day visit when the pandemic is over. I hope you enjoy the book. If you do, please feel free to make an optional donation of any amount which will go to UNICEF.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
eventName: The Road to COP26 (and Back Again)
story:
I’m delighted to announce The Road to COP26 (and Back Again), a department wide charity event running through November. The key details are as follows:

  1. The challenge: how many times can the department get to Glasgow for COP26 (c.600km) and back again
  2. The how: colleagues contribute kms by any means (e.g. walking, running, cycling, rowing, swimming) and provide evidence (e.g. via Strava, Apple Fitness, Garmin Connect) so the department’s progress can be monitored
  3. The why: to support WaterAid – an international NGO providing clean water, decent toilets and hygiene knowledge to people who don’t yet have access to them.

Why WaterAid? Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

  • Access to clean water and toilets is a human right, and should be a normal part of daily life for everyone, everywhere
  • 771 million people don’t have clean water and 1.7 billion people don’t have a decent toilet
  • 31% of schools don’t have clean water and 443 million school days are lost every year because of water-related diseases
  • Every $1 invested in water and toilets returns an average of $4 in increased productivity
  • The World Bank says promoting good hygiene is one of the most cost-effective health interventions.
  • WaterAid and COP26: Climate change is making it harder for the world’s poorest people to get clean water. WaterAid are at COP26, urging leaders to act now to fix this.
title: The Road to COP26 (and Back Again)

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
In celebration of our Golden Wedding Anniversary we have chosen to support WaterAid  

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

Graham and Rose x
